title: How to Create a Simple Alarm Clock in Python
author: Sharlene Khan
excerpt: If you're a Python beginner, this simple alarm clock is an excellent practical introduction.
summary:
If you're a Python beginner, this simple alarm clock is an excellent practical introduction. 
There are lots of exercises you could use to strengthen your Python skills. One of these exercises is an alarm clock, which you can write as a single script file. You can also run it using a command prompt. In the alarm clock script, the user needs to set the time they would like the alarm to go off. The Python script will then display a "Wake up" message to the user when the alarm goes off. You can also add a countdown to show the user how long they have to wait until the alarm goes off.

title: Compensating For Your TVs Backlight
author: Matthew Carlson
excerpt: [Pekka Väänänen] has a Panasonic TV with a broken backlight that creates an uneven pink/green color. While it isn't a huge deal for most films, black-and-white films tend to show the most eff…
summary:
[Pekka Väänänen] has a Panasonic TV with a broken backlight that creates an uneven pink/green color. While it isn't a huge deal for most films, black-and-white films tend to show the most effect. So, by modeling the distortion as a function, [Pekka] set out to find an inverse function that corrects the distortion before it gets to the TV.
However, the backlight doesn't emit enough light for some colors, which means the blue and green channels need to be dimmed. As mentioned earlier, the distortion isn't even, so the distortion needs to be captured and then calculated.

title: A Guide To Google's Knowledge Graph Search API For SEO
author: Ruth Everett
excerpt: Help your customers find you quicker than your competitors by using the Knowledge Graph and ranking better on the SERPs.
summary:
Google introduced the Knowledge Graph in 2012 to help searchers discover new information quicker.
Essentially, users can search for places, people, companies, and products and find instant results that are most relevant to the query.
The Knowledge Graph is a collection of topics, also known as entities, connecting to other entities. Entities are single information objects that can be uniquely defined.
They enable Google to go beyond just keyword matching when returning a response to a particular query.

The FBI's Internet Crime Complaint Centre (IC3) released a Public Service Announcement (PSA) warning employers and job seekers about the rising risk of deepfakes during the recruitment process.

Sure, watching startlingly accurate deepfake videos of actors like Tom Cruise can be fun, albeit a little unnerving at times.

title: Home Interiors: How to choose and care for your mattress
author: Kya Delongchamps
excerpt: Circadian science has determined that sleep 'cleans the brain' and that regular, chronic sleep interruption can have serious health impacts
summary:
Many of us don't bother to deep address a mattress issue until we drop-kick our cocoa over our spouse at 2am some Saturday night. This is outright neglect. It's estimated that every time we step out of bed, we leave behind 235ml of body fluids — a hearty mugful. Some of this revolting eau-de-you, will evaporate off, but much of it settles into the foam, fill, and ticking of the bed.

The UK Sleep Council have carried out research that indicates that an average mattress, after just two to three years, can carry worrying levels of staphylococcus, norovirus, and MRSA, sopped up by normal use.

title: Milan bounce back against Juventus to give Allegri a slap in the face
author: Nicky Bandini
excerpt: Massimiliano Allegri took the Monty Python approach to explaining Juve's latest setback after setting himself up for a fall
summary: Massimiliano Allegri threw down a gauntlet, only for his rivals to pick it up and slap him in the face with it. 'Try taking five starters away from Inter or Milan,' said the Juventus manager last month as he sought to defend his team's slow start to the Serie A season by gesturing at an extensive injury list. 'Then let's see if they run into difficulty.'Milan did indeed look diminished as they travelled to Stamford Bridge last week without Mike Maignan, Theo Hernández, Davide Calabria, Simon Kjær, Alexis Saelemaekers and Junior Messias – not to mention long-term absentee Zlatan Ibrahimovic.

title: 12 People Skills to Succeed at Work
author: Coursera
excerpt: Your ability to work well with others—or your people skills—are valuable abilities. Learn more about key people skills to feature on your resume.
summary: Working with others—and working well with others—is often a key part of many jobs. People skills, sometimes called interpersonal skills, are important traits you can develop or strengthen to create stronger relationships and improve how you work with others. As automation continues to escalate, 'the need for finely tuned social and emotional skills will rapidly grow' by 2030, according to a recent skills report from McKinsey [1]. In this article, we'll review several important people skills you can build or refine to succeed in your role.

title: Georgetown recruit Kamryn Lee-Caracci defies categorization. One of the state's top middle hitters, the Lyons senior redefines the position. ‘Kam can do so many other things.'
author: Matt Le Cren
excerpt: The 6-foot-1 Lee-Caracci can play several positions, which isn't unusual. But her ability to excel at more than one is rare.
summary:
Kamryn Lee-Caracci doesn't like stereotypes, including any about the position she plays.

The Lyons senior is one of the top middle hitters in the state and said the position doesn't get the respect it deserves.

'People always say the middles are the stupidest players, and I kind of hated getting that title, especially with how hard I work in school,' Lee-Caracci said.

If the disrespect came from another teenager, that would be one thing. But she said she heard it from a club coach, and that really got her riled up.

title: iDetect for vulnerability detection in internet of things operating systems using machine learning
author: Al-Boghdady
excerpt: Scientific Reports - iDetect for vulnerability detection in internet of things operating systems using machine learning
summary: iDetect for vulnerability detection in internet of things operating systems using machine learning Internet of Things (IoT) 's devices are ubiquitous and operate in a heterogonous environment with potential security breaches. IoT Operating Systems (IoT OSs) are the backbone software for running such devices. If IoT OSs are vulnerable to security breaches, higher-level security measures may not help. This paper aims to use Machine Learning (ML) to create a tool called iDetect for detecting vulnerabilities in C/C++ source code of IoT OSs.

title: NFL Week 5 picks, schedule, odds, injuries, stats, fantasy tips
author: ters
